# `human_overall` (1-5) is the ground truth the Evaluator is calibrated against.
# Tiers: strong ~5, mediocre ~3, weak ~1-2. Lines starting with # are ignored.
{"id": "gold-01", "question_id": "da-001", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "An INNER JOIN returns only rows where the join key matches in both tables, so unmatched rows from either side are dropped. A LEFT JOIN returns every row from the left table plus matching right-table rows, filling NULLs where there is no match. I would use INNER JOIN when I only care about records that exist in both, like orders that have a valid customer. I would use LEFT JOIN when the left table is the source of truth and I also want the non-matches visible, like listing all customers including those who never ordered."}
{"id": "gold-02", "question_id": "da-001", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "INNER JOIN gives you rows that match in both tables. LEFT JOIN gives you all the rows from the first table. You would use them depending on what data you need from the query."}
{"id": "gold-03", "question_id": "da-001", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 1, "answer": "They are both ways to combine tables. INNER is the normal one and LEFT is when you want more rows. I usually just try both and see which result looks right."}
{"id": "gold-04", "question_id": "da-002", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "Bar charts compare discrete categories, like revenue by region. Line charts show a trend over an ordered axis, usually time, like monthly active users. Pie charts show parts of a whole when there are only a few slices. A pie chart is the wrong choice when there are many categories: showing market share across 12 competitors as a pie is unreadable, and a sorted bar chart is better because people compare lengths more accurately than angles."}
{"id": "gold-05", "question_id": "da-002", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "Bar charts are for comparing things, line charts are for trends over time, and pie charts show percentages of a total. A pie chart is bad when you have too many slices to read."}
{"id": "gold-06", "question_id": "da-002", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 2, "answer": "You use whichever chart looks best for the data. Pie charts are good for most things. A pie chart is wrong if the colours are hard to tell apart."}
{"id": "gold-07", "question_id": "da-003", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "All three are window functions that number rows within a partition by an ORDER BY. ROW_NUMBER() always gives a unique sequential number even for ties, so 1,2,3,4. RANK() shares the number for ties but then skips, so 1,1,3,4. DENSE_RANK() shares for ties without skipping, so 1,1,2,3. I would use ROW_NUMBER() to get exactly one row per group, like the latest order per customer. RANK() suits leaderboards where two joint-first means no second place. DENSE_RANK() is for compact ranks with no gaps, like grading bands."}
{"id": "gold-08", "question_id": "da-003", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "ROW_NUMBER gives every row a number. RANK and DENSE_RANK are similar but handle ties differently, one skips numbers and one does not. You use them with OVER and PARTITION BY. They are useful for ranking things in groups."}
{"id": "gold-09", "question_id": "da-003", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 1, "answer": "They all rank rows. ROW_NUMBER is for rows, RANK is for ranking, and DENSE_RANK is a denser version. I would have to look up the exact differences between them."}
{"id": "gold-10", "question_id": "da-004", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "I would push back on the word engagement first, because it is too vague to track directly, and ask what behaviour actually signals value for this product. Then I would operationalise it: DAU/MAU for stickiness, active days per week, or core actions per session like reports created. The right one depends on the product's value: a meeting tool cares about minutes in calls, a dashboard tool about reports created. Pitfalls: vanity metrics that rise without reflecting value, Goodhart's law once the metric becomes a target, and confusing active with engaged. I would pair it with a retention metric so we do not optimise hollow activity."}
{"id": "gold-11", "question_id": "da-004", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "I would track engagement using something like daily active users or how often people log in. I would watch out for the metric being misleading if people log in but do not really do anything useful. Maybe also look at session length."}
{"id": "gold-12", "question_id": "da-004", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 2, "answer": "Engagement is how engaged the users are. I would measure it by counting logins and page views and report that number to the product manager. If it goes up, engagement is good."}
{"id": "gold-13", "question_id": "de-001", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "ETL extracts data, transforms it on a separate engine, then loads the clean result into the target. ELT loads raw data into the target first, typically a cloud warehouse, then transforms it there with SQL. I would choose ETL when the target has no real compute, or when transformations are heavy and unrelated to analytics. I would choose ELT with a modern columnar warehouse like Snowflake or BigQuery, because compute there is cheap, keeping raw data lets you replay transforms, and dbt and SQL are more accessible than custom transformation code."}
{"id": "gold-14", "question_id": "de-001", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "ETL is extract, transform, load, so you transform before loading. ELT loads first and then transforms. ELT is the more modern approach and is used with cloud warehouses, while ETL is the older approach."}
{"id": "gold-15", "question_id": "de-001", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 1, "answer": "ETL and ELT are basically the same thing, just with the letters in a different order. Both of them move data around between systems. I would use whichever one the team already uses."}
{"id": "gold-16", "question_id": "de-002", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "OLTP systems handle lots of small fast transactions, single-row inserts, updates and reads, and optimise for low latency and consistency. They are usually row-oriented databases like Postgres backing an application, for example an e-commerce checkout writing one order at a time. OLAP systems handle large analytical queries that scan and aggregate many rows, and are columnar stores like BigQuery or Snowflake, for example a daily revenue-per-region report over millions of rows. The two are kept separate so analytics does not slow the transactional workload."}
{"id": "gold-17", "question_id": "de-002", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "OLTP is for transactions, like an application's database doing inserts and updates. OLAP is for analytics, the big reporting queries. One is for everyday operations and the other is for analysis. Postgres would be an OLTP system."}
{"id": "gold-18", "question_id": "de-002", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 2, "answer": "OLTP and OLAP are both database types. OLTP is online transaction processing and OLAP is online analytical processing. They are both used for storing data. I think OLAP is the faster one."}
{"id": "gold-19", "question_id": "de-003", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "A primary key uniquely identifies each row in a table: its value must be unique and not null, and a table has only one, possibly spanning several columns. A foreign key is a column in one table that references another table's primary key, expressing a relationship between them. Referential integrity is the rule that every foreign-key value must point to a row that actually exists in the referenced table: you cannot reference a missing row, and the database blocks or cascades a delete when other rows still reference it."}
{"id": "gold-20", "question_id": "de-003", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "A primary key is the unique identifier for a row in a table. A foreign key links to another table's primary key. Referential integrity means the keys have to match up properly between the two tables."}
{"id": "gold-21", "question_id": "de-003", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 1, "answer": "Primary key is the main key of the table and foreign key is a key that comes from a foreign table. Referential integrity is when the database is set up correctly. They are both important for databases to work."}
{"id": "gold-22", "question_id": "behav-001", "tier": "strong", "human_overall": 5, "answer": "Last quarter our team committed to a client dashboard with a hard two-week deadline after a planning slip. I owned the data layer. I listed every component, flagged the forecasting widget as the riskiest, and decided to ship it with a simpler model first and refine later. I cut two nice-to-have filters and moved them to a follow-up, and I asked a teammate to take the QA pass so I could focus on the pipeline. We delivered on time, the client signed off, and we shipped the better forecast the next sprint. My takeaway was to triage by risk early instead of treating every task as equal."}
{"id": "gold-23", "question_id": "behav-001", "tier": "mediocre", "human_overall": 3, "answer": "There was a time we had a really tight deadline on a project. It was stressful but we worked hard as a team and managed to get it done on time. I stayed late a few times and we communicated a lot. In the end the client was happy with what we delivered."}
{"id": "gold-24", "question_id": "behav-001", "tier": "weak", "human_overall": 1, "answer": "I always work well under pressure and I am good with deadlines. I just focus and get things done. I cannot think of a specific example right now but it happens a lot and I always deliver in the end."}
